nsation in EU Law?” -- tDeveloping General Concepts and Common Principles of EU Tort Law -- tWhy Should One Size Fit All? A Call for a Differentiated Look on the Renewed European Approach Towards Private Enforcement0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTort law is one of the core areas of European private law, in particular in the field of business law. However, it often receives less attention than the well-known and widely published developments in the field of European contract law. In order to direct more attention to this important subject, an intensive Round Table discussion on the subject of the evolution of torts in European business law was held. The contributions to this volume reflect the results of the research undertaken by renowned European scholars and practitioners on central aspects such as competition law, company law and intellectual property. Each contribution particularly focuses upon the overarching tendencies and principles within the individual aspect of tort law, thereby directing attention to the future at European level of this essential area of private law. Readership: Lawyers, academics, legal departments, judges, legal professionals concerned with torts in European business law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aBar, Christian von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoom, Willem H. van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasper, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCristofaro, Giovanni De, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGussone, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinze, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id